passages.name: P2_8.1
passages.text:
Please remember, again, that I am speaking generally; I am aware there are exceptions to this.  But especially with groups like the Westboro Baptist Church being the dominant voice in the conversation, Christians cannot simply dismiss this.  If the dominant voice is hatred, we must stand up against it; we must shout louder.  Staying silent does nothing of value; it only confirms our stance is one and the same with that of animosity and stigma.
In the next section, I will discuss the Christian view of sex, gender, and marriage, and why opposition to LGBTQ+ rights still persists.  I want to make it clear at this point that I do not stand fully for one side or the other, but on both sides.  I’m part of both communities, and have parts of me on both sides.  This doesn’t make them equal; I just wanted to make my stance clear from the outset.
[[For now, let’s go over the Christian perspective.|P2_9]]

passages.name: P3_6
passages.text: Ask yourselves these questions: 1. Do the words I use respect the personhood of LGBTQ+ people? 2. Do the words I use describe being LGBTQ+ as a choice? 3. Do the words I’m using have positive, negative, or neutral connotations? 4. Am I using a derogatory slur to refer to LGBTQ+ people? Even if this slur has been reclaimed by the LGBTQ+ community, why am I specifically using this word, what right do I have to use it, and what benefit does it bring to the conversation? (The answer to those last two things is usually none.) 5. Am I respecting all members of the LGBTQ+ community with the words I have chosen? 6. If I'm talking about a person in the LGBTQ+ community, am I using the correct pronouns? 7. Are there any harmful stereotypes I am perpetuating with my language? [[I hope this helps.|P3_7]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.text: Also, this essay will discuss Christianity and LGBTQ+ rights as it pertains to the United States, as that is where I am from and where the issues I have observed specifically take place.  When I talk about “the Christian community” or “the LGBTQ+ community”, you can be sure that I am speaking of those communities as they exist in the United States.  That’s not to say the content of this essay can’t apply to other places, of course, but I wanted to make the central location clear from the outset to avoid confusion. passages.name: P2_9
passages.text:
The conclusion most Christians I’ve met reach on the ideas of the gender spectrum, gender expression, etc. is that God made two genders (male and female) during creation for a reason, and those two genders are all that exist.  Specifically, Adam and Eve of Genesis hold a symbolic place for most Christians (and represent many things, but I’ll try to only list the things relevant to this conversation), not only as the first humans created, but as the first romantic couple and marriage union.  [[They were created for each other, man and woman, and those genders and bodies were created to be together.|P2_10]]  This is why you get signs and phrases like “It’s Adam and Eve, not Adam and Steve” in opposition to gay marriage, and why the first response against transgender people is something akin to, “Well, God doesn’t make mistakes; they can’t really be in the wrong body.”

[[Today, LGBTQ+ youth and adults are still stigmatized in America, and especially by the Christian community, in similar ways to the (mid-)1900s.|P2_8.1]]  Young people are kicked out of their homes for coming out; conversion therapy is the go-to option to “fix” gay youth; Christian groups and churches refuse to recognize the genders of transgender and gender-nonconforming individuals; these are just a few things, but I think you get the point, and I’ll stop here for brevity’s sake.
In the Christian community, anything LGBTQ+ related is completely treated like taboo, and individuals who are LGBTQ+ are greatly stigmatized.

(That’s as brief a summary as I can make.  I strongly encourage you to look into the topic for yourself.  Here’s a short list of Google-able terms for you: Stonewall, Marsha P. Johnson, ACT UP, Sylvia Rivera, Gay Liberation Front.
If you think something needs to be added to the list, feel free to let me know!
Also, for those who may be thinking, “But it wasn’t just Christians who were hateful during the AIDS crisis,” or, “But some Christians helped the LGBTQ+ community,” I regret to inform you that you’re missing the point.  Responding immediately with “not all Christians” indicates a willingness to ignore past mistakes by the community and brush aside the sinful actions of those who claim[ed] to belong to God.  Hatred isn’t a contest or a game of golf where the lowest score “wins”; if we are hateful, we must acknowledge that hate, apologize for it, and change our behavior.  If we are a part of a group claiming to love, but that promoted hatred in a nation’s darkest hour, we must own up to that, recognize the terrible actions of those who claim[ed] to follow Christ, and try to change.  I’ll discuss this more in a later section.)
Some people might be saying, “But that was in the past!  What does any of it have to do with today?”

My thesis in understanding any activist group today (specifically as they pertain to liberal politics in the United States, but this can be applied most anywhere) will always be this: to understand their cause and goals, you must first understand history and how it has shaped them, whether positively or negatively.  In my view, “left-wing” politics are an active rebellion against hatred and prejudices in the United States (which came to a particular rise in the 1900s), striving for equality in a country that has changed since those groups formally came together, but still discriminates in various areas.  This includes feminism, racial politics, and—yes—[[LGBTQ+ rights.|P2_6]]

passages.name: P2_4
passages.text: Even if we believe someone’s hatred to be misunderstood, we still must confront that hatred. Ignoring it in the hope that the other side “gets over it” (which is not the same as giving someone space) is entirely the wrong approach to me, whether in a personal relationship or a nationwide one. We must open a healthy discussion, understand why the other side doesn’t like us, and set things straight. This starts on an individual level, but it must start. Some Christian groups and people have done this, to be entirely fair. But overall, not enough has changed, and I see an unwillingness to approach the hatred of the LGBTQ+ community, and a dismissal of the roots of that hatred—a root that is still active and growing today, and was not founded on misunderstood hate. [[So where did this root come from? passages.text: Part 2: Christianity & LGBTQ+: The Divide [[The Christian community and the LGBTQ+ community have clashed for many years.|P2_1-1]] Today, there is overall still an attitude of disdain from the Christian community to the LGBTQ+ community, and vice versa. There has been change, and some positive development in improving the attitude both sides have for each other, but overall the contempt remains. What I have found is this: the majority of Christians don’t fully understand the LGBTQ+ community; like I used to be, all they know is the L, G, B, and T, and there’s much more than that; furthermore, anything LGBTQ+-related is taboo in the church, and not discussed. On the other side, the LGBTQ+ community has mostly rejected the Christian community because of their past hatred, present attitude, and unwillingness to understand. ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.name: p1
passages.text: Prologue: My Testimony—Who I Was and How God Got Me Out Let’s flashback to me, Naomi Norbez, high school student. Severely depressed, long-time thief, and, most importantly and most tragically, a habitual liar since kindergarten. You ask me a question, I don’t tell you the answer: I tell you a lie you want to hear, without even thinking or processing you even asked a question until a second later. That’s my reality every day, of every hour, with every question asked: one lie after the other, with no way to stop myself from doing it without everything I’ve said crashing down. Stealing and deception is also a problem for me. When I was five I stole some of the other kids’ toys from show-and-tell, and it grew into a huge temptation to take things, or have other people buy me things and weasel my way out of paying them back. I also swear like a sailor. Lots of that running around in my head at all times, along with a very negative inner voice. It’s the first thing I hear when I wake up and the last thing I hear when I go to sleep. [[Here’s my story.|p2]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Return to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 1-->|P1_1]]

passages.name: P2_18
passages.text:
You can see where things can get conflicted.
The fact is, being part of the LGBTQ+ community is still a radical act.  Yes, even here in 2017.  Queer history is a painful one, a struggle for rights that has lasted many decades, and is finally starting to get some headway.  [[This is nicely and brutally summarized in this magnificent poem by J. Egan—please read it; it’s an excellent poem, and summarizes things far better than I ever could.|https://spondee-soliloquy.tumblr.com/post/151678338341/seventeen-things-you-have-to-learn-for-yourself]]
[[Being queer is an act of rebellion.|P2_19]]  It’s standing by one’s self, even in the face of hatred and ignorance and fear-mongering.  It’s being part of a history marked by righteous anger.  It’s radical.

passages.name: P1_1.3
passages.text:
I had also been raised to see anything other than a heterosexual relationship as wrong.  I was called gay in school once because I refused to date at age 11, and when I asked my parents what it was, they told me first that it meant “happy” (which confused me more) then told me the meaning of the word today.  My knowledge was extremely limited (and I use “limited” in a neutral way here), shaped by my Christian upbringing to see anything other than a man and a woman together as wrong.
[[To be fair to my parents, though, I doubt they could have imagined how prominent LGBTQ+ rights would be today.|P1_2]]

passages.name: P1_1.2
passages.text:
Back then, though, [[I barely knew anything about the LGBTQ+ community.|P1_1.3]]  I knew about lesbian, gay, and transgender people, and I knew that they existed, but that was about it.  
I had read some fiction with transgender characters as a young adult, which had introduced me to transgender people in the first place, but all the books I’d read were written by cisgender authors, and mainly focused on gender dysphoria as its main struggle for the characters.  
Because of this, I was taken to the conclusion that to be a transgender person meant an active, intense struggle against one’s body to be the gender that they felt they were since they were a very young child, and taking active, physical steps to be the person they knew they were.  While that image is true for some, it is not true for all; my perception was warped by the fiction I read.
------------------------------------------------------

passages.name: P3_4.1
passages.text: "Transgenderism" is a stance on transgender people that disrepsects their genders. After all, if being trans is just a condition that can change, why call transgender people by the correct pronouns? Why give merit to what they say about gender dysphoria? If it's just an "-ism", then it can change, and we can give every excuse not to give transgender people any ground when they discuss gender and sex. I know that may sound super paranoid, but this is the implication of the language we've chosen. I've seen it in action before. [[By constantly relying only on the term “transgenderism” when discussing transgender people, we disrespect transgender people by saying their gender a choice that can be undone.|P3_5]] And while, yes, the movement for LGBTQ+ rights is a movement that one can choose to be a part of, the act of being LGBTQ+ is, on the whole, not a choice. ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.name: e5
passages.text:
Jesus would never hold a sign saying “God Hates F-gs”.  The Jesus I know from the Bible would reach out to transgender youth, go to gay bars to chat and share a few parables, and listen to those who ask why God made them this way.  And for the people holding picket signs, he would call them not real followers of His, and condemn them to hell.
If Christians really want to change the legacy of hatred toward the LGBTQ+ community, we must first start by rediscovering who Jesus is, who he ministered to, and why he came.  [[We must focus on the heart of Jesus and become like him; we must not become so caught up in hatred.|e6]]

passages.name: e4
passages.text: As Christians, we are called to love, to protect the disadvantaged and bring hope to the hopeless. Dismissing non-cis people’s gender identities as “just a phase” or “a deception” or “confused” is a disservice to them, and presents Jesus’s people as a people of hostility and rejection. As sad as that is, that is the community of Christians we are right now, and that is the thing we must change—not just to clean up our image or our reputation, but to clean the biases and rejection from our minds, to [[demonstrate real love as Jesus would.|e5]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 4|P4_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: demonstrate real love as Jesus would.

passages.name: e6
passages.text:
The Jesus I know called me so I could love, speak truth in love and use that love to comfort the hopeless and oppressed.  That is my mission: to love people as they are, to demonstrate Christ with my actions, to share the gospel with my actions as well as my words.  If that is not your Jesus, then please consider you may not be following him, but one created inside of your mind, a rule-stickler God-man who wants to see creation perfect again, and will push people around to make that happen.
[[We must remember what true love is.  And we must uphold the word of God always.|fin]]

passages.name: e1
passages.text: Epilogue . . . I really wanted to be more conclusive in this essay. I wanted to take a very firm stance either for or against gay marriage & LGBTQ+ rights, and detail why I stood on one side or the other. But after researching and musing and pondering everything, digging deep into these topics these last few months (and even longer, for the last few years), I’m still standing basically in the middle. [[I have parts of me in both sides, because this isn’t a black-and-white issue—it’s a collage of grey, a painting of human colors representing many different topics.|e2]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 4|P4_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: I have parts of me in both sides, because this isn’t a black-and-white issue—it’s a collage of grey, a painting of human colors representing many different topics.

passages.name: e3
passages.text: When I discuss with other Christians the rights of transgender and gender-nonconforming people, I mostly find a rigid attitude, and this saddens me. I find people who believe transgender people are lying or deceived, and that anyone who thinks that they aren’t a straight, cisgender male or female is wrong in their thinking. This viewpoint is pretty damaging in my view. In invalidates people’s personal experiences and forces them into one of two categories, which they may not be totally comfortable with. [[Most importantly, it is a viewpoint that favors upholding the sanctity of God’s creation strongly over God’s call to Christians to love others.|e4]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 4|P4_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: Most importantly, it is a viewpoint that favors upholding the sanctity of God’s creation strongly over God’s call to Christians to love others.

passages.name: e2
passages.text:
I believe that all human beings have a right to love and a right to be loved.  I also know that deception to sin is completely possible.  After reviewing both the traditional and revisionist arguments, I’ve found validity in both, and I can’t deny that.  If you were looking for a strong “yes” or “no” in this piece, well, I don’t think I’m at a place to stand fully on one side of the issue, at least not yet.  Maybe I’ll have a stronger stance after further study.  The only stance I have right now is one rooted in empathy, various scripture readings, and the desire to educate fellow Christians about these topics.
[[I’ll close with this.|e3]]

passages.text:
Christianity is an act of rebellion.  It’s standing by a Messiah who called us to forsake everything to follow him, who ate with the worst people in his day, who loved like no one else and didn’t stand for hypocrisy and high-horse attitudes.  It, too, is radical.
The difference is this. LGBTQ+ puts self-love and the right to love is at the center of their movement.  Christianity teaches that, in order to truly be free, one needs to realize their unholiness in God’s eyes, and follow Christ in pursuit of that holiness.
[[I know those are very simple summaries, but I hope they capture the heart of both communities.|P2_20]]

passages.name: P2_13
passages.text: I’ll say this once: We as Christians are not called to marriage; we are called to serve God. And whether that leads to marrying someday or leads to a life of singleness, both are equally good. This is something we as a church need to understand, because marriage is still put on a crazy high pedestal. To be fair, I’m aware that singleness is also treated like “last place” by the culture as well, but that’s all the more reason for the church to remember and promote singleness as equally valid. So what are Christians called for in their sexual life, if not marriage? Well, to borrow a term from Christopher Yuan, Christians believe they are called to “holy sexuality”. But what is holy sexuality? Let us define what that means. Actually, let’s go one step back, and [[define what it means to be “holy”|P2_14]]. Because holiness is at the heart of all of this. ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.name: P2_12
passages.text: This is likely why conversation therapy exists in the first place, to take gay people away from their “unnatural urges” and make them heterosexual (which would, in [sadly] many Christian minds, naturally lead to marriage), whether they like it or not. (Side note: Our extreme emphasis on marriage and rejection of sex outside marital bonds also leads to problems in how we’ve approached sex workers. Relatedly, this increased the stigma against gay people in the ‘80s AIDs crisis, as many had frequent sex and multiple partners which led to them getting infected with HIV, and the Christian community turned away in disgust. That’s an essay for someone else to write, not me [as I’m not super knowledgeable in this area, nor am I speaking from personal experience], but I just wanted to bring that up.) [[Singleness is not often seen as a valid option in the Christian life; the attitude from many seems to be that if you’re a Christian, you’re going to get married eventually.|P2_13]] This is why telling gay and lesbian people who join the church to “just stay single” is seen as a cop-out and an invalid response: the church has put so much emphasis on marriage and forgotten singleness as an equally valid option, that telling anyone to “just stay single” seems to be telling them to be lesser in the eyes of God and the church. ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: Singleness is not often seen as a valid option in the Christian life; the attitude from many seems to be that if you’re a Christian, you’re going to get married eventually.

passages.name: P2_11
passages.text: Finally, marriage holds a special place in the heart of the Christian. We believe marriage is the only place for a sexual relationship, any sex outside the bonds of marriage is wrong because sex was made for those who are married to enjoy, and that marriage is between a man and a woman. Of course, there’s nothing wrong with marriage, not at all. But to take an argument from [[Christopher Yuan|http://www.christopheryuan.com/mobile/bio.html]] when I heard him speak ([[he has a good video about responding to the LGBTQ+ community, btw|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wupEp1RDDjg]]), Christianity has put marriage on a very, very high pedestal, to the point of making it an idol. Biblically, singleness and marriage hold the same validity; both are good in their own way. [[But the church promotes marriage more often than not, and sees singleness as last place, or as “the waiting stage” for marriage.|P2_12]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.name: P2_10
passages.text: Also, in some places/denominations, [[modern Christianity puts a strong emphasis on male leaders, becoming a sort of patriarchy|P2_11]] (I’ve especially seen this in churches/denominations in the southern United States, but I’m sure you can see it places in the north as well. I will also wholly admit to being ignorant of some denominations and Christian sects). Men lead the church; women help in the background. Both are “supposed” to fulfil their expected gender roles; those who step outside them are a confusion. To be clear and fair, men as leaders and women as servants is a biblically founded idea, and there’s nothing generally wrong with it, but it has been taken to unfair extremes, used to wrongly box people (especially women) into their roles. ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.name: P2_17
passages.text: Traditional views argue for the relevance of Scripture as a holy, timeless book. Regardless of the historical context, we need to follow the Bible’s word on homosexuality: that it is sinful, and that those who engage in anything same-sex related are sinning. It argues that the Bible is infallible and all inspired by God, and that while Christians are not under the law, the law is holy and has good things in it. Revisionist views argue for the fallibility of Scripture interpretation over time. These views look closer at the historical context of the verses (why was this law given in Leviticus? Was Rome in particular a place with promiscuous homosexual activity, prompting Paul to write about it in Romans 1? Etc.), as well as the historical context of certain translations of scripture (King James especially, at least in the sources I’ve read), and the original Hebrew and Greek. It argues that while the Bible is indeed an infallible and holy book, the people translating and interpreting it are not, and those people have led us to dishonest and harmful conclusions about homosexuality. [[Traditionalists see Revisionists as people who bend over backwards to find a satisfactory word on homosexuality in the Bible. Revisionists see Traditionalists as people who refuse to change their stance even in the face of mounting evidence.|P2_18]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: Traditionalists see Revisionists as people who bend over backwards to find a satisfactory word on homosexuality in the Bible.  Revisionists see Traditionalists as people who refuse to change their stance even in the face of mounting evidence.

passages.name: P2_16
passages.text: The biblical passages on homosexuality are as follows: Genesis 19, Leviticus 18:22, Leviticus 20:13, Romans 1:26-27, 1 Corinthians 6:9-10, and 1 Timothy 1:10. There are many passages in the Bible that also discuss marriage and romantic relationships, but these six are the passages that directly talk about homosexuality (though Genesis 19 is somewhat debated on this point). At this point in the essay, I originally planned to dissect those passages and take a side. But during my research, I found many, many people who have picked these verses apart it far better and in far more detail than I ever could. [[So I’ll just give you some things here for you to check out|Biblegaylinks]], and [[summarize the traditional and revisionist viewpoints on these “big six” homosexuality passages.|P2_17]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

With this in mind, “holy sexuality” means viewing love, relationships, and sex in a way that is pleasing to God.  It means approaching relationships in a way that is godly.
This is most of the reason that Christians, overall, reject gay marriage.  It doesn’t fit into the mold of holy sexuality, and does not seem to be what God intended for His people. passages.name: P2_14
passages.text: To be holy simply means “to be set apart”. Imagine I have five pens. I take one pen, put it in a drawer, and lock it away. That one pen is now “set apart”. It is, by definition, holy. But what has it been set apart to do? Perhaps I put it aside for writing only special letters and invitations. Or only for special drawings, not everyday doodles. Or for calligraphy. The pen has been set aside for a purpose. This is the heart of the Christian life: we believe, as holy people of God called by Jesus Christ, we have been set aside for a holy purpose. And that purpose is to bring others to Jesus Christ, by living like Christ daily. Living like we have a heavenly home beyond Earth, and a Father in heaven who is waiting for us and has called us to live by a different path: a path of holiness and love. This means not living like other people live. And this calling effects every aspect of life: how we spend money, how we talk, how we write. [[And yes, how we have sex.|P2_15]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: And yes, how we have sex.

passages.name: P4_5-1
passages.text: Honestly, I think Christians kind of deserve to be spit in the face. We’ve not done enough good to the LGBTQ+ community, and we need to do better by them. The biggest problem with our religion is that it can be misread as an excuse to commit hateful acts—and it has, many times! It’s not Christianity-as-a-religion’s fault, but those who bear our name are our problem—and the problem of everyone else, and especially those they hurt. [[We are known as a group of hurtful, hateful people, the last thing Jesus Christ is all about. This is a tragic and somewhat sickening thing.|P4_6]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: We are known as a group of hurtful, hateful people, the last thing Jesus Christ is all about.  This is a tragic and somewhat sickening thing.

passages.text: These words are not gospel. These words are not fact, though they are supported by facts. They are the thoughts and opinions of one struggling soul hoping to reach other struggling souls. I firmly believe in the merit of those who struggle in public, because those who struggle in public can help those who struggle in private. That is why am writing this, to reach out to folks and teach people, to help those like myself who wonder if the LGBTQ+ community and the Christian community can ever reconcile, if at all. The way fellow Christians talk about LGBTQ+ issues has been a constant issue everywhere I've gone. [[I've wanted a piece that talked about Christianity & LGBTQ+ issues in broad strokes. I couldn't find one, so I made one.|3]]

passages.name: P2_20
passages.text:
The problem in Christianity rises when things get twisted.  When holiness is pursued by removing any and all hint of unholiness in the church, and putting restrictions on who can even enter.  When empathy is discarded for adherence to a set of restriction and rules.
We focus so much on Roman 1’s “anti-homosexual” message that we don’t see Roman 2’s message of hope, of Paul talking about how the gospel is for all people, and that the message of Christ gives hope to every human being.
One thing the church should not be is hateful.  And yet, that is how we are seen by the LGBTQ+ community—and it’s a valid view, because of our hateful attitudes.
[[And one of the key parts of this is how we discuss LGBTQ+ issues.|P3_1]]

passages.name: P4_6-1
passages.text: This is a common theme that comes up with most discussions with groups outside the Christian community, not just in discussions with the LGBTQ+ crowd: I’ve seen Christians demonize the other party and/or refuse to listen to them. Part of this is because of negative stereotypes believed about the other party that are assumed during the discussion, but overall it is because of that misunderstanding, seeing questioning core beliefs as an instant attack, when that is not always true. It should be assumed to be false if we are to get anywhere. [[We should not deny those who question—on the contrary, it is extremely important as a church body that people are allowed to exercise doubt without being condemned. This is something we are not known for doing well, but it needs to be a key, visible part of Christianity’s heart.|P4_7]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.text: Finally, let me say from the outset: You are always free to contact me if you have any questions, thoughts, or concerns; whether you see flaws in my argument, agree or disagree with me entirely, believe I got some of my facts wrong (I am a fallible human just like you, after all, and I am not a professional minister of any sort) or are struggling to understand my points, you are free to contact me.\n[[Let’s start a conversation.|7]]

passages.name: P2_6
passages.text: LGBTQ+ Americans have faced discrimination for decades. This came to a major head with the AIDS pandemic of 1980s, where thousands of LGBTQ+ people died of the HIV virus in the United States. The most tragic thing about the AIDS pandemic is that it should not have been a pandemic—if the government acted sooner, had treated the disease with the seriousness it deserved in its early stages, many lives could have been saved. President Reagan did not treat the disease with the alertness needed to counteract it; he actively obstructed progress in fighting it, and many believe (and have proof to believe) that it is because the main victims of the disease were LGBTQ+ that he did not take it seriously, and stayed silent as thousands died. It is important to remember that Ronald Reagan was Catholic, had been elected on a religious voter base, and voiced opposition for same-sex marriage throughout his presidency, in defense of traditional marriage. Furthermore, the Christian response to the disease was, to say the least, absolutely repulsive. Many said that the LGBTQ+ community was getting what they deserved for their sin—that is, death. AIDS (called “gay cancer”) was called God’s wrath against LGBTQ+ people, punishment against them for their unnatural acts (same-sex relationships). Instead of love and help, those sick with AIDS were stigmatized and pushed away. [[Churches would not take in sick people or help care for them, and the LGBTQ+ community was left to fight for themselves to find a cure, forming groups such as ACT UP.|P2_7]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: Churches would not take in sick people or help care for them, and the LGBTQ+ community was left to fight for themselves to find a cure, forming groups such as ACT UP.

passages.name: p2
passages.text:
It’s summer.  Mom signs me up for Bible camp.  I was raised in a Christian home, so this kind of thing is normal, but I have no want to go.  Until I look on my shelf, and find my Bible: it’s dusty, and I brush off the cover.  It makes me realize how much I’ve changed, how far I am from God.  Things feel impossible to change at this point; I keep lying, the negative thoughts in my head keep screaming, and I don’t know what to do.  I want to be close to God again, like I was when I was younger.
I pull a devotional from my shelf—a devo I only happen to have because of a “mystery box” I bought years ago.  “Ok God,” I pray when I’d finished reading the first chapter.  “Here’s the thing.  I don’t know how to change.  If I’m gonna find you at this camp, you need to help me stop swearing.  I really need these voices out of my head,” I beg.
[[I go to sleep.|p3]]

passages.name: p3
passages.text: Next day, I wake up. Something has changed. All the words and voices that were screaming at the forefront of my mind—for years--was now in the back, a low murmur with no power over me. It was like waking up with a whole different mind. It’s not something I can explain on my own—I had tried to change by my own power many times before, but nothing happened; I’d remained the same. [[It was God. Plain and simple.|p4]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Return to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 1-->|P1_1]]

links.text: It was God.  Plain and simple.

passages.name: Biblegaylinks
passages.text: Joe Dallas, leader of the ex-gay movement, is a strong supporter of the traditionalist view. Not only does his book with Nancy Heche, The Complete Christian Guide To Understanding Homosexuality, give strong arguments and refute the revisionist perspective, it's also a very good guide to LGBTQ+ issues in general. It's quite a large book, but each chapter has a short summary, along with links for further reading. Dallas is also the author of The Gay Gospel? How Pro-Gay Advocates Misread the Bible. On the other side is God and the Gay Christian by Matthew Vines, a book I have read of in many places (blog posts, articles, opinion pieces, etc), but haven't gotten to read yet myself. I know it's a strong supporter of the revisionist view of the Bible, and the idea that God is alright with gay relationships that are committed marriages. For more, [[please see my resource page.|resources]]

passages.name: p4
passages.text: Long story short, I came back to Christ at that Bible camp. God changed me up, big time: I stopped lying, became an honest person who stole no more. That first moment when I came back home, and my mother asked me a question, and I was able to actually STOP, pause, and then tell the TRUTH, well. One of the best moments of my entire life. I try to cling to this moment, those few weeks that changed my entire life, the weeks that all that “Jesus stuff” I’d heard since I was a child really, truly clicked. I’ve had mountains and valleys in my faith, and I still experience depression to this day. But I try to remember that I am a child of God, that in hopeless times, He is the one I should cling to. [[That is my testimony.|index]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Return to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 1-->|P1_1]]

passages.name: P2_3
passages.text: At a Christians conference I attended over the summer, I heard some speakers say that Christians don’t really hate LGBTQ+ people—LGBTQ+ people just think we do because of prominent hate groups like the Westboro Baptist Church, a group who pickets with signs like “God Hates F-gs”. It’s “the gays” (LGBTQ+ people were called that multiple times) who have to see that Christians are actually loving people, not the “haters” Westboro makes us out to be! And if we wait long enough, maybe they’ll finally see what we’re really like, and come to us. Speaking as a fellow Christian who agrees that Westboro is a huge problem and they do not represent Christian love: [[No. Just no.|P2_4]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 1|P1_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 3-->|P3_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.name: P4_11
passages.text:
The Christian church’s message to them has been, and still is, “Your right to love and exist is denied, unless you adhere to the model we want you to follow.”
Which is funny, because Christ’s message is, “You don’t need to change for me.  Trust me and follow me, know that I saved you and love you unconditionally.  Give up yourself and be part of me.  [[And I’ll change you along the way.|e1]]”

passages.name: P1_2

Jump forward to 2015.  I had already made friends with a fellow game developer who identified as transgender then, and we made a comic together.  They asked if one of the characters in the comic’s universe (who didn’t make it into this particular comic) could be agender, something I had no idea existed.  This (as well as a video I made that my friend commented on) is what first made me realize that [[there was more to the LGBTQ+ community than I thought, and that I was severely lacking in knowledge on the topic.|P1_2.1]]

passages.name: P1_3
passages.text:
Because of the black-and-white Christianity views gender (which will be discussed in greater detail later in this essay), I’ve been very hesitant to publically identify myself as anything other than a cisgender female.  But, especially in light of the LGBTQ+ representation in my short story collection, I feel I should explain myself.
[[I identify as nonbinary|P1_3.1]], which is a pretty broad term, but in my case means I am neither male nor female, but a mixture of both genders.  I was born female, but I feel more masculine than feminine, and tend to express myself as such.  I am comfortable with they/them pronouns, though I go with she/her more often than not.
------------------------------------------------------
[[<--Back to Prologue|p1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 2-->|P2_1]]

passages.name: P1_4
passages.text: I struggle to come to terms with my identity for multiple reasons. For one, I often wonder whether my masculine identity formed as a result of trauma in my past. I was severely bullied by male classmates during grade school, with the bullying continuing at a lesser degree until I was in high school. After grade school (where I made one male friend in third grade), I didn’t have a positive relationship with a male classmate until I was 14 years old. That’s almost ten years of schooling where my relationships with male classmates was either negative or neutral. It resulted in androphobia when I was an adult (which has since lessened significantly, but was particularly troubling for me as a young adult). Because of this, I sometime wonder if my nonbinary-ness is a result of mental trauma, whether my need to become more masculine (something I did a lot when I was a child and teenager, by copying my father in many things) came out of a need to be a “strong man” instead of a “weak girl”, to defeat the bullies who tormented me because of my gender by becoming more male. And if my gender identity did form this way, whether it can be “cured” or lessened, like a mental illness. [[If it can simply disappear, leaving nothing but femininity behind, then coming out as nonbinary would only be a tedious act, meaningless if ones gender identity will only “change” or “revert”; this makes me anxious and hesitant to come out.|P1_5]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Prologue|p1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 2-->|P2_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: If it can simply disappear, leaving nothing but femininity behind, then coming out as nonbinary would only be a tedious act, meaningless if ones gender identity will only “change” or “revert”; this makes me anxious and hesitant to come out.

passages.name: P1_5
passages.text:
But when I ponder this, I can also think of counterexamples and objections to the argument.  I remember small exceptions to my relationships to male classmates, a few good (if not short) relationships here and there, hidden by the prominence of trauma.  I also know that the adults who influenced me most as a child were mostly female (the major exceptions being my father and male family members, of course), and that my biblical upbringing taught me to love and respect both genders.
Lastly, I remind myself that the term “nonbinary” is just that: a term, a label.  I struggled to find a term that fit me before I found nonbinary, and that’s a perfectly fine thing in my view.  The way we see ourselves can change, and the terms we use to see ourselves can change too.  
[[And that’s completely ok.|P1_6]]
------------------------------------------------------

passages.name: P1_6
passages.text: In a sense, this is a “chicken or egg” question: Did my need to become more masculine rise out of my experiences? Or was that need already in me to begin with, and was perhaps heightened by my childhood traumas? This is something I still don’t have a definite, solid conclusion for. Some days I feel confident about my gender identity; other days, I feel very unsure and irresolute, sometimes depressed. [[Overall I’m glad to have the nonbinary label, as it makes me make sense in a way I hadn’t understood until now.|P1_7]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Prologue|p1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 2-->|P2_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

As for everyone else: please, for goodness sake, don’t use this section to disregard the gender identity of those who have experienced trauma like I have.) ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Prologue|p1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 2-->|P2_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

But even more than my past traumas, the biggest reason I am uncertain about my gender identity is because of the Christian views of gender and Christianity’s attitude toward the LGBTQ+ community.  [[To fully understand this, we must dissect what those attitudes are and how they affect people, both in positive and negative ways.|P2_1]]

passages.text:
And while we’re talking about choice and gender, it’s important to note that the Christian community’s approach to LGBTQ+ issues is strongly based in what I’m going to call “LGBTQ+-ism”.  
[[That may sound weird, but bear with me.|P3_8]]
------------------------------------------------------

passages.name: P3_4
passages.text: I’ve seen many people in the Christian community who really, really want to believe that transness is a choice someone makes (I’ll talk about this more in a bit). I remember asking a gentleman for his thoughts on the rights and identities of transgender people, and his response was, “Well, let me put it this way: would you believe me if I said that I identified as a six-foot-tall pink elephant?” [[And I’ve heard lots of similar things from people, that imply that transness is a choice, an act of imagination, a deception, something that can be reversed with effort.|P3_4.1]] I didn’t wake up one morning and “decide” to be nonbinary. And no transgender person has “become” their gender by “deciding” to be trans one day. ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: And I’ve heard lots of similar things from people, that imply that transness is a choice, an act of imagination, a deception, something that can be reversed with effort.

passages.name: P3_5
passages.text:
That was a really close look at just one term I’ve seen in Christian circles concerning the LGBTQ+ community, and there are many other terms like it.
(It’s probably important to mention at this point that a member of the LGBTQ+ community using certain terms [ex: “queer”] is not the same as the Christian community (or any community) using those terms against them.  Reclaiming language is a whole other topic, and I don’t think I’ll be going into it here, but I wanted to bring that up.)
The main reason I dissected “transgenderism” is to demonstrate how the language used by the church to describe the LGBTQ+ community short-sells them, and to encourage straight, cisgender Christians reading this to [[examine the language they themselves use when talking about the LGBTQ+ community (or any other group, for that matter).|P3_6]]

"Transgenderism" a popular way for Christians to refer to transgender individuals; it was even used in the recent [[Nashville Statement|https://cbmw.org/nashville-statement/]] (see Article 10), a document detailing the Christian evangelical response to the LGBTQ+ community’s beliefs on sex and gender.  I usually see “transgenderism” used instead of “transgender people” when reading Christian texts.
And I’ve personally never seen “transgenderism” used in LGBTQ+ community circles.  [[There’s likely a good reason for that.|P3_3]]

passages.text:
The suffix “-ism” is defined as “denoting a system, action, principle, condition, movement, or process” (this definition is a mix of definitions from [[GlobalRPh|http://www.globalrph.com/medterm5c.htm]] and [[Google|https://www.google.com/search?q=-ism+meaning&oq=-ism+meaning&aqs=chrome..69i57.548j0j7&sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8]].  On its own, “ism” is defined as “a distinctive practice, system, or philosophy, typically a political ideology or an artistic movement”.
Why does this matter?  Well, keeping in mind the definition of “-ism”, “transgenderism” can be defined as (1) something someone decides to have and act upon, (2) a condition or movement which therefore can be changed, (3) a belief of philosophy, etc.  You get the idea, I believe.  [[“Transgenderism” mostly implies that being a transgender individual is a choice someone actively makes.  Not something someone is.|P3_4]]  It makes transness into a choice, into a movement one can join if they decide to, and thus implies that such choices in life can be reversed.

passages.name: P3_1
passages.text: Part 3: Communication and Language in Christian Circles The language Christians use when discussing LGBTQ+ issues is so important. I personally feel that the words we currently employ can be demeaning and have negative connotations. [[We’d be here all day if I discussed every single term or phrase, so I’ll use the term “transgenderism” as an example, and use it to discuss broader issues of language and communication.|P3_2]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: We’d be here all day if I discussed every single term or phrase, so I’ll use the term “transgenderism” as an example, and use it to discuss broader issues of language and communication.

passages.name: P3_8
passages.text:
I've seen a desperate need in Christian circles to find the "cause" of peoples' same-sex attraction or non-cisgender-ness.  LGBTQ+ people and issues are discussed as if being LGBTQ+ is a choice that one can find some way to reverse, that there’s a metaphorical off-switch buried in someone’s heart that they haven’t yet found.  The idea that being gay, or transgender, or bisexual, or nonbinary, or whatever, is always a choice that a person made somewhere along the way, consciously or not.
[[And honestly, I think this approach really reveals the church’s insecurities and discomfort with LGBTQ+ people.|P3_9]]  It’s a desperation to find the magic button that will “make the gay go away”.  It’s the belief that everyone is given a burden to bear for a reason, or a struggle with sin for a reason, and that it can be overcome someday; that’s a fine belief on its own, but when applied to LGBTQ+ people things get murky.
------------------------------------------------------
[[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]]
[[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: And honestly, I think this approach really reveals the church’s insecurities and discomfort with LGBTQ+ people.

passages.name: P3_9
passages.text: And the heart of this is because we want to know why God did this. We do this for our benefit, trying to find the "reason" people were given this "burden". It’s seeing being LGBTQ+ as being weighted with sin, but also being degenerate, somehow at fault by nature of being associated with non-cis-straightness, and thus being “worthy” (I use that word sarcastically) of Christian judgement because something in their life(style) must have made them queer, right? That’s the main message the LGBTQ+ community is getting from us: the church’s discomfort and quick-to-judge attitude. [[“LGBTQ+-ism”—the idea that all LGBTQ+ people are the way they are by choice and all have the power to change but don’t—is the most vocal Christian stance on LGBTQ+ people.|P3_10]] Add to that the judgmental stance toward the LGBTQ+ community that is also the most vocal Christian stance, and you’ve got a very bad combination that, frankly, smells of ignorance. ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: “LGBTQ+-ism”—the idea that all LGBTQ+ people are the way they are by choice and all have the power to change but don’t—is the most vocal Christian stance on LGBTQ+ people.

passages.name: P4_9
passages.text: It’s not just about marriage when it comes to gay rights and the Christian community. It about Christians repeatedly telling LGBTQ+ people, “You’re not allowed to love. You are wrong for wanting love and wanting to love.” It’s about the stigma surrounding any topic relating to love, sex, and gender in the church. [[We need to erase that stigma and learn to talk about these things honestly and openly, for everyone’s sake.|P4_10]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: We need to erase that stigma and learn to talk about these things honestly and openly, for everyone’s sake.

passages.name: P4_8
passages.text: And I know, I know seeing the human side of these things can be seen as the wrong Christian approach—being too “worldly” and not “godly” (see John 17). I happen to be a person with a high amount of empathy, and that has everything to do with how I approach this particular topic. If I wasn’t personally part of this, I feel my stance would be near the same. It’s important to recognize what Christianity really is when you boil it down: a commitment to following God and being Christ-like to all people. Yes, we are called to not be of the world. But we are not called to hate the world or the people in it. Unfortunately that seems to be the approach taken to LGBTQ+ topics. We should not stand for this. We as a church can change. We’ve changed before. [[We must change our discomfort with LGBTQ+ issues—we can’t be afraid to get uncomfortable.|P4_9]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: We must change our discomfort with LGBTQ+ issues—we can’t be afraid to get uncomfortable.

passages.name: P4_5
passages.text:
Simply put, “the gay agenda” (read: those fighting for LGBTQ+ rights and gender/sex education, or just those daring to exist as an LGBTQ+ person) is one striving for acceptance.  It’s a movement rooted in anger against the rejection, discrimination, and abuse LGBTQ+ people have faced for decades and are still facing today.  It’s a movement that spits in the face of the hatred (of Christians) and says to all seeking identity, “[[You are welcome, and you are valid—no matter what anyone else says.|P4_5-1]]”
------------------------------------------------------
[[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]]
[[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: You are welcome, and you are valid—no matter what anyone else says.

passages.name: P4_4
passages.text: Perhaps you’ve experienced it. Desperation to find something, anything to reconcile the “abominable” love with following God. Which has led to the reevaluation of scripture passages that discuss homosexuality, in an attempt to find a connection with God that makes sense. Because what people hear from the church is often not enough. They’re desperate for answers, but they usually don’t get them. [[They’re looking for bread, but the church hands them a promise of hellfire and lets them starve.|P4_4-1]] Or gives them nothing at all because we don’t like talking about sex and gender. Because we’re only comfortable with people who fit our predetermined descriptions of a Christ-follower and church-goer. ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: They’re looking for bread, but the church hands them a promise of hellfire and lets them starve.

passages.name: P4_7
passages.text: We should also not assume the other party is here to attack. I’ve seen those who refer to the gender binary as “an attack” on traditional views of gender, sex, and marriage; LGBTQ+ issues are treated like a virus that we need to purge from the church. That view ignores the heart of those who feel outside their assigned gender, the questions they may wonder about themselves and others like them. When they are labeled “attackers”, it demeans them and dehumanizes them, encourages them to step away from the Christian faith that calls them an “attack”. I hear terms like “the gay agenda” and “the attack on traditional marriage”; we make people into an agenda. We don’t see people as people when we do that. [[We miss the human side of this.|P4_8]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: We miss the human side of this.

passages.name: P4_6
passages.text: When beliefs that contradict the Christian doctrines come into a discussion (say, a reinterpretation of some Levitical verses about homosexuality), the natural inclination I’ve seen is for Christians to get defensive, to shut down discussion, and reject both the individual and their argument. This is because we equate discussing our core beliefs to dismantling/disproving our core beliefs, and those things are not equal to each other. When people ask questions, they usually genuinely want answers. It is extremely important to open discussion with people who disagree with us, and [[avoid demonizing or shaming them throughout that discussion.|P4_6-1]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: avoid demonizing or shaming them throughout that discussion.

passages.name: P4_1
passages.text: Part 4: Hungry for Hope There’s a popular reading of Christianity that interprets sharing the hope of the gospel as “one beggar telling another where to find bread”. That Christ’s good news is a nourishing source for every person, who needs it desperately even if they don’t think they do. If the gospel is the bread, then we’ve been starving the LGBTQ+ community. They’ve turned to other sources for nourishment. They don’t want our food anymore. [[Why is that?|P4_2]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.name: P4_3
passages.text: One emotion really sticks out to me in this zine: a feeling of raging desperation. People desperate to just be able to romantically love the only way they know how, but also follow Jesus Christ. They’re desperate for something, anything to bring it together, to reconcile themselves. It’s a theme present in every piece. [[And that desperation is present outside the zine too.|P4_4]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 3|P3_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Epilogue-->|e1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: And that desperation is present outside the zine too.

passages.name: P4_2
passages.text:
I’ve looked over a lot of Biblical commentaries and opinions while writing this piece.  I’ve read both “revisionist” (pro-LGBTQ+ views) perspectives and “traditional” (pro-traditional-marriage) views.  [[So many people trying to make sense of their sexual identity within the scriptural text, taking note of the context of the passage and writing out what they see as its meaning today, or standing by original interpretations of passages about homosexual activity, seeing the passages forbidding it as still standing as is in today’s world.|P4_2-1]]

passages.name: P3_14
passages.text:
LGBTQ+ people are feared because of stereotypes and misconceptions.  There are so many of them.  
That transgender women are actually men playing dress-up to leer at girls.  That gay men are pedophiles.  That gay people are promiscuous and want to get in the pants of their same-sex friends.  That all lesbians are predatory.  That all who experience same-sex attraction went through some horrible trauma; that transgender people were molested and that caused their gender dysphoria; that LGBTQ+ people were raised without a prominent mother or father figure in their lives and that made them who they are; that trans people are faking it for attention.
[[So many misconceptions.  I could list more, but I’ll stop here.  Writing it out pains my heart.|P3_15]]
------------------------------------------------------
[[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]]
[[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: So many misconceptions.  I could list more, but I’ll stop here.  Writing it out pains my heart.

passages.name: P3_15
passages.text: Some of those, as bad as they are, may be true of a few LGBTQ+ people. But on the whole, these are misconceptions for a reason: they’re harmful stereotypes that only serve to put LGBTQ+ people in a box of shame before our conversation with them even begins. We must approach discussion free of stereotypes and misconceptions. We need to come to conversations with LGBTQ+ people as . . . well, conversations with people. And I don’t mean people to solely feel sorry for because of their orientation either. Approach these things with a blank slate. [[Assume nothing, listen to everything. Every LGBTQ+ person is different.|P3_16]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: Assume nothing, listen to everything.  Every LGBTQ+ person is different.

passages.name: P3_16
passages.text: And every LGBTQ+ person deserves respect from us. Whether that be using the right pronouns, or approaching discussions with them with no misconceptions, or changing the words we use when talking about LGBTQ+ things, they deserve respect from us. [[People hear the language Christians use when we talk about LGBTQ+ issues and the people in that community. We need to change the texture of our discussion, and remove disrespectful language, phrases, and assumptions.|P4_1]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: People hear the language Christians use when we talk about LGBTQ+ issues and the people in that community.  We need to change the texture of our discussion, and remove disrespectful language, phrases, and assumptions.

passages.name: P3_10
passages.text: It’s the reason why conversion therapy (basically legal torture from all the accounts I’ve read—no, I’m not exaggerating [and no, I am not speaking from personal experience here]) exists at all, because of our conviction that queerness can be changed if people put work into it, and the lingering belief that being LGBTQ+ is equivalent to being mentally ill. That if people identified the root cause of their sexual orientation and/or gender, if they just put effort into being straight and/or male or female, then they’d change. [[Because, despite everything about the Christian message, we still believe in some ways that people did something to deserve whatever life they have; that if people haven’t changed, it’s their fault for not trying hard enough; and that there is a root cause why people are LGBTQ+.|P3_11]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: Because, despite everything about the Christian message, we still believe in some ways that people did something to deserve whatever life they have; that if people haven’t changed, it’s their fault for not trying hard enough; and that there is a root cause why people are LGBTQ+.

passages.name: P3_11
passages.text:
Look, don’t think I’ll ever know why I was born in a woman’s body but feel more like a man.  When I get to heaven, maybe I’ll ask (I doubt it’ll matter much there, though).  But while I’m on Earth, the best thing you can do for me and all LGBTQ+ folks is to treat them with respect—not like a burden, not like a person who’s “faking it”, not like someone who hasn’t tried hard enough to change.
[[We need to treat LGBTQ+ people lovingly.  Is that so much to ask?|P3_12]]
------------------------------------------------------
[[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]]
[[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: We need to treat LGBTQ+ people lovingly.  Is that so much to ask?

passages.name: P3_12
passages.text: The reason why the LGBTQ+ community doesn’t generally like to mingle with Christians is because of how we have communicated with them and treated them over the years. People leave the church because the church doesn’t make them feel welcome. It always baffles me when I see fellow Christians scratching their heads and asking, “Why doesn’t the LGBTQ+ community like us?” Well, it’s no wonder they don’t like us; we’ve encouraged them to keep their dirty sexed-and-gendered selves away from our precious chapel. We’ve put preserving an idea holiness over actually being holy. [[And that’s a tragedy.|P3_13]] ------------------------------------------------------ [[<--Back to Part 2|P2_1]] | [[Go to Index|index]] | [[Go to Part 4-->|P4_1]] [[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

passages.name: P3_13
passages.text:
I remember when the HB2 “Bathroom Bill” were being reviewed in North Carolina.  These bills would deny transgender people access to the bathroom that matched their gender, and require them to use the restrooms of their biological sex (or the sex on their birth certificate, if they had sex reassignment surgery).  Trans women were specifically targeted when these bills were on the table.
A lot of senators and representatives came forward and said the main reason they supported these bills were to keep men away from their mother/sister/daughter/insert-token-vulnerable-female-here.  This was the biggest, most vocal argument for the necessity of HB2.
[[It was—and is—an argument rooted in fear-mongering.|P3_14]]
------------------------------------------------------

links.text: It was—and is—an argument rooted in fear-mongering.

passages.name: P2_1-1
passages.text: LGBTQ+ people also are redefining the Bible in ways most Christians are not fully comfortable with: proposing that the some people in the Bible might have been gay, that the famous “abomination” verses in Leviticus may not have be speaking to all gay men, and so on.  The discomfort of Christians toward this usually results in anger and a shutdown of conversation.  Because of all these things and more, both groups have only moved further apart.\nPlease keep in mind I am speaking in generalities.  I’m well aware there are exceptions to everything I’ve said, and more exceptions are arriving every day because of changing attitudes toward the LGBTQ+ community (which is overall a wonderful thing to see).  [[But overall, this fog of disdain is still prominent, and it’s a huge problem.|P2_2]]\n[[Link to LGBTQ+ Glossary|http://www.algbtical.org/2A%20GLOSSARY.htm]]

links.text: But overall, this fog of disdain is still prominent, and it’s a huge problem.
